   <h1 align="center"> 
Attorney General Ellison calls for national recall of theft-prone Hyundai/Kia vehicles </h1>
   
<p class="lede">Joins coalition of 18 AGs in asking NHTSA to recall vehicles while AG continues to investigate whether companies have violated Minnesota law</p>
<p class="lede">Thefts of Hyundai and Kia vehicles dramatically higher in metro area, leading to deaths and other violent crimes</p>

  
 
     <p><strong>April 20, 2023 (SAINT PAUL)</strong>Â â Minnesota Attorney General Keith Ellison today joined a coalition of 18 attorneys general in calling for a federal recall of Hyundai and Kia vehicles, following the companies&rsquo; continued failure to take adequate steps to address the alarming rate of theft of their vehicles. In aÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/docs/KiaHyundai_Ltr_to_NHTSA.pdf" target="_blank">letter</a>Â to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA), Attorney General Ellison and the coalition requests NHTSA to institute a recall of unsafe Hyundai and Kia vehicles manufactured between 2011 and 2022 whose easily bypassed ignition switches and lack of engine immobilizers make them particularly vulnerable to theft. Â </p>
     
     <p>The letter that Attorney General Ellison and the coalition wrote to NHTSA comes in the context of his office&rsquo;s<a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/03/07_KiaHyundai.asp" target="_blank">Â ongoing civil investigation</a>Â into whether Hyundai and Kia haveÂ violated Minnesota&rsquo;s consumer-protection and public-nuisance laws in failing to equip their vehicles with industry-standard anti-theft technology. Today&rsquo;s letter also comes afterÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/03/02_KiaHyundai.asp" target="_blank">Attorney General Ellison, Minneapolis Mayor Jacob Frey, and Saint Paul Mayor Melvin Carter wrote directly to the North American presidents of the two car companies in March</a>Â to ask them toÂ immediately recall and outfit all Kia and Hyundai vehicles missing industry-standard anti-theft technology, in order to stem the rapidly rising tide of vehicle thefts in the Minneapolis/Saint Paul metro area. TheirÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/docs/KiaHyundai_Ltr.pdf" target="_blank">letter</a>Â highlights a drastic increase in Kia and Hyundai auto thefts over the past year, including an 893% increase in Minneapolis and a 611% increase in Saint Paul. Many of these thefts have been connected to other violent crimes.Â Â Â </p>
     
     <p>InÂ <a href="https://www.ag.state.mn.us/Office/Communications/2023/docs/KiaHyundai_Ltr_to_NHTSA.pdf" target="_blank">today&rsquo;s letter</a>, Attorney General Ellison and the coalition of attorneys general have now called on the federal government to step in, as the vehicles&rsquo; systems remain out of compliance with federal standardsÂ and pose an unreasonable risk to public safety, and the companies have failed to address these safety issues.Â </p>
     
     <p>&ldquo;The massive increase in thefts of Hyundai and Kia vehicles have Kia and Hyundai have more than enough time to fix this problem voluntarily. It&rsquo;s now time for the federal government to step in and mandate recall of these vehicles,&rdquo; Attorney General Ellison said. &ldquo;In the meantime, I&rsquo;m continuing my civil investigation of Kia and Hyundai and the ongoing threat to public safety they have failed to fix. I&rsquo;m using the tools of civil law to help keep Minnesotans safe.&rdquo; Â </p>
     
     <p>Between 2011 and 2022, Hyundai and Kia chose not to include anti-theft devices that were a standard feature in almost every other new car manufactured during that time period, including the same Hyundai and Kia models sold in Canada and Europe. Hyundai and Kia owners now face unnecessary risk of having their vehicles stolen, as well as related concerns, like struggling to obtain insurance for the affected vehicles.Â </p>
     
     <p>These vehicles have been stolen at high rates since approximately 2021, harming consumers and contributing to an erosion of public safety. The thefts have frequently been accompanied by reckless driving and further criminal activity, causing injuries and deaths. The thefts have even gone viral, withÂ <a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2022/09/08/tiktok-challenge-spurs-rise-in-thefts-of-kia-hyundai-cars.html" target="_blank">videos on social media</a>Â showing how to hotwire these vehicles and challenging others to steal them. Following these videos, thefts began surging across the country.Â Â </p>
     
     <p>Attorney General Ellison and the coalition assert that Kia and Hyundai have not gone far enough in their attempts to remedy their vehicles&rsquo; vulnerability to theft. While the companies have offered a software upgrade, this upgrade will not be available for many affected vehicles until June and for some 2011-2022 models cannot be installed at all. Vehicle owners who cannot receive the software upgrade can reportedly receive a free steering wheel lock from Kia and Hyundai, but this places additional burdens on owners and does not address the underlying ignition system flaw that makes the vehicles so vulnerable to theft. Many owners have contacted NHTSA for assistance with this theft issue.Â </p>
     
     <p>In the letter, the states urge NHTSA to take immediate action by instituting a recall of the unsafe Hyundai and Kia vehicles because:Â </p>
     
     <ul type="disc">
       <li>The vehicles violate federal requirements that vehicles have a starting system that prevents the activation of the engine or motor and steering system when the key is removed;Â </li>
       <li>The Hyundai and Kia vehicles&rsquo; vulnerability to hotwiring and theft has created an unreasonable and well-documented risk to safety on U.S. roads;Â </li>
       <li>Surging thefts of unsafe HyundaiÂ andÂ Kia vehicles have consumed law enforcement and emergency responder resources; andÂ </li>
       <li>The companies&rsquo; response through a phased and voluntary service campaignÂ is insufficient to protect drivers and the general public.Â </li>
     </ul>
     
     <p>Attorney General Ellison joins a coalition led by California Attorney General Rob Bonta and includes the attorneys general of Arizona, Colorado, Connecticut, the District of Columbia, Illinois, Massachusetts, Maryland, Michigan, New Jersey, New Mexico, New York, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and Washington.</p>
